WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.419 --> 00:00:03.450
Hello, everyone. Welcome to a new episode of the

2
00:00:03.450 --> 00:00:06.489
Center. I'm your host, as always, Ricardo Lopez, and

3
00:00:06.489 --> 00:00:09.890
today I'm joined by Doctor Ian James Kidd. He's

4
00:00:09.890 --> 00:00:13.239
an associate professor at the Department of Philosophy at

5
00:00:13.239 --> 00:00:16.729
the University of Nottingham and today we're talking about

6
00:00:16.729 --> 00:00:21.010
philosophical misanthropy. So, Doctor Kidd, welcome to the show.

7
00:00:21.049 --> 00:00:22.879
It's a huge pleasure to everyone.

8
00:00:23.290 --> 00:00:25.489
Thank you, Ricardo. Pleasure to be here. Looking forward

9
00:00:25.489 --> 00:00:26.290
to our conversation.

10
00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:31.159
OK, so let's start perhaps with the most basic

11
00:00:31.159 --> 00:00:36.599
question here. So, what is philosophical misanthropy? And since

12
00:00:36.599 --> 00:00:41.650
we are talking the uh philosophical take on misanthropy,

13
00:00:41.799 --> 00:00:46.380
how does it differ from the way people commonly

14
00:00:46.889 --> 00:00:48.639
talk about misanthropy?

15
00:00:49.860 --> 00:00:52.090
Well, there's a distinction I want to draw between

16
00:00:52.090 --> 00:00:57.299
philosophical and vernacular misanthropy. So in everyday vernacular language,

17
00:00:57.380 --> 00:01:01.439
misanthropy means something like a hatred or a distrust

18
00:01:01.439 --> 00:01:04.819
or contempt for human beings, maybe individuals or the

19
00:01:04.819 --> 00:01:08.339
collectives. And I want to say that at best

20
00:01:08.339 --> 00:01:11.629
is one extreme kind of misanthropy. So in the

21
00:01:11.629 --> 00:01:14.489
philosophical sense, misanthropy is not defined as a set

22
00:01:14.489 --> 00:01:17.900
of emotions. It's a judgment or a verdict on

23
00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:21.989
the moral condition of human beings. Like any verdict

24
00:01:21.989 --> 00:01:24.989
or judgment, it will express itself in certain emotions,

25
00:01:25.190 --> 00:01:27.830
but misanthropy in its philosophical sense is a judgment.

26
00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:32.309
It's a verdict based on evidence, reasons, arguments, assessments,

27
00:01:32.690 --> 00:01:34.559
um, and I think there's quite a big difference

28
00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:37.430
between the philosophical and the vernacular sense of misanthropy.

29
00:01:37.910 --> 00:01:40.069
Because if you ask someone, are they a misanthrop,

30
00:01:40.230 --> 00:01:42.069
they'll usually say, no, I don't, I don't hate

31
00:01:42.069 --> 00:01:45.540
people. I don't feel contempt for human beings. Um,

32
00:01:45.550 --> 00:01:47.750
AND that makes them think that misanthropy is, it's

33
00:01:47.750 --> 00:01:50.930
not a position to endorse, whereas in the philosophical

34
00:01:50.930 --> 00:01:53.449
sense, if you ask, do you think that humankind

35
00:01:53.449 --> 00:01:56.430
collectively is morally pretty dreadful, I think more people

36
00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:57.919
will be inclined to answer yes.

37
00:01:59.580 --> 00:02:03.629
Right. And, and why would anyone be a misanthrope?

38
00:02:03.779 --> 00:02:07.309
I mean, what are the reasons behind that?

39
00:02:08.419 --> 00:02:10.657
Well, it, it varies a lot by the individual

40
00:02:10.657 --> 00:02:14.018
misanthrope. I mean, some people describe themselves as natural

41
00:02:14.018 --> 00:02:17.328
born misanthropes, and they'll claim that they've always had,

42
00:02:17.479 --> 00:02:20.768
uh, some vague feeling that humankind is pretty dreadful,

43
00:02:20.998 --> 00:02:22.979
that the human world is full of cruelty and

44
00:02:22.979 --> 00:02:26.018
greed and injustice. Um, AND there might be such

45
00:02:26.018 --> 00:02:29.639
people who've always had that pre-philosophical sense that our

46
00:02:29.639 --> 00:02:32.488
moral condition as a species is pretty bad. Uh,

47
00:02:32.619 --> 00:02:35.298
BUT the misanthropes I'm interested in, they usually come

48
00:02:35.298 --> 00:02:39.690
to their misanthropy through a combination of. Um, EXPERIENCES

49
00:02:39.690 --> 00:02:43.490
of their own, usually bad experiences, um, certain kinds

50
00:02:43.490 --> 00:02:47.479
of reflection on humankind in our moral performance. Um,

51
00:02:47.570 --> 00:02:50.520
THEY might have had what can't cause long, sad

52
00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:54.500
experience of the ingratitude, injustice, and cruelty that seems

53
00:02:54.500 --> 00:02:56.660
to infect the human world. Some of them might

54
00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:59.580
have been inspired by certain arguments, including arguments given

55
00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:02.619
by the philosophical misanthropes. Uh, FOR other people it

56
00:03:02.619 --> 00:03:05.279
might be the inspiration of, of philosophical or religious

57
00:03:05.279 --> 00:03:07.979
tradition, um, because I think many philosophies and religions

58
00:03:07.979 --> 00:03:11.690
have misanthropic, um, components. And maybe for other people

59
00:03:11.690 --> 00:03:13.809
it's, it's probably some combination of all of these

60
00:03:13.809 --> 00:03:15.559
things. I mean, at least in my own case,

61
00:03:16.130 --> 00:03:19.089
I wouldn't describe myself as a natural born misanthrope.

62
00:03:19.410 --> 00:03:23.570
I remember being fairly sort of optimistic, uh, romantic,

63
00:03:23.649 --> 00:03:27.020
philanthropic, wanting to think the best of people. But

64
00:03:27.020 --> 00:03:28.970
in my case it was a combination of lots

65
00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:33.300
of philosophical work on vices and wickedness and evil,

66
00:03:33.679 --> 00:03:35.770
and then it was reading books about misanthropy by

67
00:03:35.770 --> 00:03:39.289
modern philosophical misanthropes like David Cooper, uh, or David

68
00:03:39.289 --> 00:03:43.440
Benatar. And then using those philosophical ideas to rethink

69
00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:46.080
certain experiences and and learning to look at the

70
00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:49.240
world again in a different way. And for me

71
00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:51.559
that process was fairly quick. It took about a

72
00:03:51.559 --> 00:03:54.320
year to become converted to misanthropy. For some people

73
00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:56.589
it's much longer, for some people it's much slower.

74
00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.250
And a lot of people also resist their misanthropy.

75
00:03:59.570 --> 00:04:02.320
Um, THERE'S a great paper by um Catherine Norloch,

76
00:04:02.399 --> 00:04:05.039
the Canadian philosopher. And she points out that many

77
00:04:05.039 --> 00:04:08.419
people have misanthropic thoughts and ideas and feelings, but

78
00:04:08.419 --> 00:04:10.339
they want to resist them. Maybe because they're not

79
00:04:10.339 --> 00:04:13.779
persuaded by the arguments, maybe because they are um

80
00:04:13.779 --> 00:04:18.100
slightly disturbed by the content of misanthropic ideas, or

81
00:04:18.100 --> 00:04:20.579
they're aware that becoming a misanthrope would damage some

82
00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:22.820
of their values or some aspects of their identity

83
00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:25.820
that mattered to them. And I think there's, there's

84
00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:28.380
quite a range of conversion processes that make a

85
00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:31.059
person a misanthrope. But what's crucial for the philosophical

86
00:04:31.059 --> 00:04:33.929
misanthrope is. At least a lot of that conversion

87
00:04:33.929 --> 00:04:36.320
is done by reasons and arguments and evidence.

88
00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:43.320
Mhm. Is there an emotional component to being a

89
00:04:43.320 --> 00:04:46.980
mis a misanthrope? I mean, what kinds of emotions

90
00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:52.489
do misanthropes experience toward humanity? I'm not saying that

91
00:04:53.309 --> 00:04:57.950
even if there's that emotional component, it is necessarily

92
00:04:57.950 --> 00:05:03.380
very relevant to philosophical misanthropy, but what could you

93
00:05:03.380 --> 00:05:04.459
tell us about that?

94
00:05:06.489 --> 00:05:08.329
Well, the, if you look at the testimonies of

95
00:05:08.329 --> 00:05:10.970
misanthropes, that they always mention an extreme range of

96
00:05:10.970 --> 00:05:14.489
emotions, um, and they usually emphasize pretty negative emotions.

97
00:05:14.529 --> 00:05:18.309
So, for example, Kant and Schopenhauer talk about sadness,

98
00:05:18.489 --> 00:05:24.290
woe, disappointment, frustration, uh, the Buddha mentions dispassion, disgust,

99
00:05:24.299 --> 00:05:28.690
and anxiety, and, and I think these, these misanthropic

100
00:05:28.690 --> 00:05:32.209
emotions, they appear in a misanthropic process of conversion

101
00:05:32.209 --> 00:05:35.309
in different stages. So it's clear that many misanthropes

102
00:05:35.309 --> 00:05:38.429
begin their journey of conversion through certain negative moral

103
00:05:38.429 --> 00:05:42.230
emotions. They feel fear, um, at the, the evils

104
00:05:42.230 --> 00:05:45.600
that human beings do. They feel grief and anxiety.

105
00:05:45.709 --> 00:05:48.869
They feel worry and loss and disappointment, and those

106
00:05:48.869 --> 00:05:52.149
emotions can help to motivate a person to start

107
00:05:52.149 --> 00:05:55.609
thinking in misanthropic ways. But over time, as your

108
00:05:55.609 --> 00:05:59.010
misanthropic verdict starts to sink in. Then I think

109
00:05:59.010 --> 00:06:01.529
a further set of emotions comes in, because when

110
00:06:01.529 --> 00:06:04.609
people come to a misanthropic judgment on humankind, they

111
00:06:04.609 --> 00:06:07.850
often experience a further set of emotions. Anger is

112
00:06:07.850 --> 00:06:13.000
often mentioned, distrust, uncertainty, sometimes shame at being part

113
00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.399
of such a dreadful species, certain kinds of sadness

114
00:06:16.399 --> 00:06:18.890
and regret at the, at the way that humankind

115
00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:22.839
has developed. And one function of philosophical misanthropy, I

116
00:06:22.839 --> 00:06:26.160
think, is to guide people through these emotional processes,

117
00:06:26.239 --> 00:06:27.839
which can be very difficult and for some people

118
00:06:27.839 --> 00:06:32.519
very traumatic. I mean, there's real moral disorientation in

119
00:06:32.519 --> 00:06:36.279
becoming a misanthrope, and most misanthropes need good guidance

120
00:06:36.279 --> 00:06:39.720
on how to manage and regulate these emotions. And

121
00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:42.399
I think there can be sometimes positive emotions as

122
00:06:42.399 --> 00:06:45.359
well. For example, certain misanthropes report a sense of

123
00:06:45.359 --> 00:06:48.670
relief at finally seeing human beings for what they

124
00:06:48.670 --> 00:06:51.390
are. Um, BUT it's pretty clear to me that

125
00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:55.899
most misanthropes find it a very difficult emotional process,

126
00:06:55.989 --> 00:06:58.790
becoming and being misanthropic, especially if you want to

127
00:06:58.790 --> 00:07:01.869
sustain your misanthropy into the long term, then you

128
00:07:01.869 --> 00:07:04.910
have to identify what kinds of negative emotions you're

129
00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:08.390
susceptible to, develop ways of coping with them. And

130
00:07:08.390 --> 00:07:11.149
that will usually involve some readjustment of your values,

131
00:07:11.269 --> 00:07:14.329
your ideals, your expectations, your habits, your ways of

132
00:07:14.329 --> 00:07:16.630
relating to other people. And that I think is

133
00:07:16.630 --> 00:07:19.309
part of the difficulty of being a misanthrop. It's

134
00:07:19.309 --> 00:07:22.839
emotionally turbulent for most people, and that requires real

135
00:07:22.839 --> 00:07:23.459
management.

136
00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:30.079
So give us some examples of what misanthrops consider

137
00:07:30.079 --> 00:07:33.679
to be the failures or the moral failures of

138
00:07:33.679 --> 00:07:34.399
humanity.

139
00:07:35.579 --> 00:07:38.459
Well, I think there are for most misanthropes historically

140
00:07:38.459 --> 00:07:40.820
and cross-culturally, I think that there are, there are

141
00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:43.859
3 main routes into misanthropy. Um, THE first route

142
00:07:43.859 --> 00:07:47.809
is reflecting on how human beings treat non-human animals,

143
00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:51.500
and the failings people mention there include, uh, greed,

144
00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:58.140
selfishness, malevolence, cruelty, brutality, exploitativeness, uh, willing to exercise

145
00:07:58.140 --> 00:08:01.239
power over other creatures. Uh, A second way into

146
00:08:01.239 --> 00:08:04.119
misanthropy is a reflection on how we relate to

147
00:08:04.119 --> 00:08:05.989
and treat the natural world. So there are eco

148
00:08:05.989 --> 00:08:09.320
misanthropes. Uh, THEY mention some of the same failings

149
00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:13.440
like greed and destructiveness, but they also mention hubris,

150
00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:19.190
mindlessness, recklessness, stupidity, short-sightedness. And then the third way

151
00:08:19.190 --> 00:08:21.679
into misanthropy is reflection on how we treat other

152
00:08:21.679 --> 00:08:25.589
human beings. And here the failings include greed, jealousy,

153
00:08:25.750 --> 00:08:32.940
malevolence, selfishness, betrayal, treachery, insouciance, lack of care, callousness,

154
00:08:33.308 --> 00:08:36.380
and one task for the philosophical misanthrop is to

155
00:08:36.669 --> 00:08:39.658
look at these different routes into misanthropy. And then

156
00:08:39.658 --> 00:08:42.388
try to map out the kinds of vices and

157
00:08:42.388 --> 00:08:45.658
failings that are common to each path. So in

158
00:08:45.658 --> 00:08:49.299
David Cooper's book Animals and Misanthropy, he identifies, I

159
00:08:49.299 --> 00:08:53.018
think, 7 clusters of failings that people often display

160
00:08:53.018 --> 00:08:54.939
in the ways that they think about animals, how

161
00:08:54.939 --> 00:08:57.018
they treat animals, and so on. And you can

162
00:08:57.018 --> 00:08:59.379
do a good bit of moral philosophy by taxonomizing

163
00:08:59.379 --> 00:09:02.299
these failings. Now there is a lot of consistency

164
00:09:02.299 --> 00:09:06.460
across different misanthropes. For example, everyone mentions greed, hatred,

165
00:09:06.630 --> 00:09:12.140
stupidity, dogmatism, malevolence, selfishness. Uh SOME misanthropes also point

166
00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:14.530
to different kinds of failings that other misanthropes don't

167
00:09:14.530 --> 00:09:17.340
mention. For example, for some people, there are aesthetic

168
00:09:17.340 --> 00:09:19.849
or spiritual failings as well, that should be part

169
00:09:19.849 --> 00:09:23.369
of a condemnation of human beings. Uh, SOME misanthrops,

170
00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:26.059
um, like to give very systematic lists. So if

171
00:09:26.059 --> 00:09:30.260
you read the Buddha's discourses, he gives enormously elaborate

172
00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:33.380
lists of the cankers, taints and defilements of human

173
00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:37.179
beings, and they're systematized, numbered and analyzed in exhaustive

174
00:09:37.179 --> 00:09:40.929
detail, whereas in other traditions they content themselves with

175
00:09:40.929 --> 00:09:44.299
looser, less systematic lists. Um, SO if you look

176
00:09:44.299 --> 00:09:47.099
at a, a recent misanthrope like Giacomo Leopardi, the

177
00:09:47.099 --> 00:09:49.700
Italian misanthrope, he doesn't give a list of the

178
00:09:49.700 --> 00:09:53.859
failings of humankind. He just gives examples um of

179
00:09:53.859 --> 00:09:56.179
the failings of human beings and how they show

180
00:09:56.179 --> 00:09:58.700
up in human life. So there's, there's no exhaustive

181
00:09:58.700 --> 00:10:01.820
and definitive list. Um, ON my computer somewhere, I

182
00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:03.820
have a list of the vices and failings that

183
00:10:03.820 --> 00:10:07.520
Misanthrope's list. I think I stopped at 500. Um,

184
00:10:07.700 --> 00:10:10.010
SOME of them have names like greed and cruelty.

185
00:10:10.179 --> 00:10:12.049
Some of them don't have names at all yet.

186
00:10:12.539 --> 00:10:15.000
Um, AND that's another task for a moral philosopher,

187
00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:17.960
is trying to identify failings that we, we can

188
00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:20.799
tune into but that we haven't described and also

189
00:10:20.799 --> 00:10:24.559
trying to identify failings that are not yet studied

190
00:10:24.559 --> 00:10:28.080
and analyzed. I call these esoteric failings, um, and

191
00:10:28.080 --> 00:10:30.039
one contribution of philosophers has been to give us

192
00:10:30.039 --> 00:10:33.369
vocabularies for thinking about these failings. Um, SO there's

193
00:10:33.369 --> 00:10:36.130
no definitive list, and there is huge variation in

194
00:10:36.130 --> 00:10:39.450
part because your condemnation of humankind will reflect your

195
00:10:39.450 --> 00:10:42.609
sense of what the ideals and values of humankind

196
00:10:42.609 --> 00:10:45.210
should be. And one of the reasons that misanthropes

197
00:10:45.210 --> 00:10:47.809
disagree with one another, they disagree about what's wrong

198
00:10:47.809 --> 00:10:50.659
with us, um. And that, that is one of

199
00:10:50.659 --> 00:10:53.119
the reasons I think that philosophers should study misanthropy.

200
00:10:53.330 --> 00:10:55.229
Even if you don't want to be a misanthrope,

201
00:10:55.409 --> 00:10:57.250
I think it's a really useful way into doing

202
00:10:57.250 --> 00:10:59.530
a kind of moral, social and political philosophy.

203
00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:07.229
So when misanthropes pass moral judgment on humanity as

204
00:11:07.229 --> 00:11:12.349
a whole, are they also doing it on individuals

205
00:11:12.349 --> 00:11:12.979
or not?

206
00:11:13.770 --> 00:11:15.650
No, I, I think one of the mistakes people

207
00:11:15.650 --> 00:11:17.570
make about misanthropy is to think that it's a

208
00:11:17.570 --> 00:11:21.289
judgment on individuals. So in the vernacular sense, misanthropy

209
00:11:21.289 --> 00:11:24.239
is a hatred or distrust of individual human beings.

210
00:11:24.619 --> 00:11:25.969
Uh, BUT, but I, I think that's a mistake.

211
00:11:26.130 --> 00:11:29.179
Philosophical misanthropy is a verdict passed on something more

212
00:11:29.179 --> 00:11:32.690
abstract and more collective, like humankind, human forms of

213
00:11:32.690 --> 00:11:35.130
life, human existence. So this is the way that

214
00:11:35.130 --> 00:11:38.780
David Cooper characterizes misanthropy. It's a judgment on. Something

215
00:11:39.309 --> 00:11:42.780
broader and more collective, humankind, human forms of life,

216
00:11:43.049 --> 00:11:47.309
the institutions, practices, structures, the systems of ambitions and

217
00:11:47.309 --> 00:11:49.989
desires that have come to characterize human forms of

218
00:11:49.989 --> 00:11:53.630
life. Now that is consistent with the misanthrope having

219
00:11:53.630 --> 00:11:56.789
specific views on individuals. For example, there will be

220
00:11:56.789 --> 00:12:00.909
certain individual human beings who stand out as exemplars

221
00:12:00.909 --> 00:12:03.809
of our collective failings. You might, so you might

222
00:12:03.809 --> 00:12:05.760
point to a certain person, maybe a political leader,

223
00:12:05.809 --> 00:12:08.570
and say that, you know, they are a living

224
00:12:08.570 --> 00:12:13.729
symbol of the greed, cruelty and indifference that characterizes

225
00:12:13.729 --> 00:12:16.640
human life. So for the misanthrope, certain individuals are

226
00:12:16.640 --> 00:12:19.770
exemplars of our collective failings. They are all that's

227
00:12:19.770 --> 00:12:22.210
wrong with us, or all that's wrong with patriarchy,

228
00:12:22.250 --> 00:12:25.200
or all that's wrong with capitalism in human form.

229
00:12:25.919 --> 00:12:28.210
But likewise, there can be certain individuals who stand

230
00:12:28.210 --> 00:12:31.179
out because they are exemplars of virtues. These people

231
00:12:31.179 --> 00:12:34.190
will stand out as morally admirable because they are

232
00:12:34.190 --> 00:12:36.969
relatively free of the failings of our collective forms

233
00:12:36.969 --> 00:12:40.169
of life. But it's crucial for philosophical misanthropy. The

234
00:12:40.169 --> 00:12:43.000
judgment is being passed on something abstract like human

235
00:12:43.330 --> 00:12:46.530
forms of life or human existence. Now one complication

236
00:12:46.530 --> 00:12:50.340
is. Does that include a judgment being passed on

237
00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:54.809
human nature? Because in Western kinds of philosophical misanthropy,

238
00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.780
it's been very common to include human nature as

239
00:12:57.780 --> 00:13:00.929
part of a condemnation. Uh, FOR example, Bernard Williams,

240
00:13:00.989 --> 00:13:04.400
uh, at one point remarks that Lutheranism is misanthropic

241
00:13:04.739 --> 00:13:07.460
because of its conceptions of human nature as corrupted

242
00:13:07.460 --> 00:13:12.179
by original sin. And I think that in some

243
00:13:12.179 --> 00:13:14.729
traditions it will make sense to include human nature

244
00:13:14.729 --> 00:13:16.750
if it's part of your way of thinking. But

245
00:13:16.750 --> 00:13:19.260
if you look at, say, the philosophical misanthropies of

246
00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:22.679
India and China. They don't pass judgment on human

247
00:13:22.679 --> 00:13:24.460
nature at all. So you can have it, you

248
00:13:24.460 --> 00:13:27.099
can have misanthropy without human nature. And I think

249
00:13:27.099 --> 00:13:30.979
in part because misanthropic verdicts are consistent with either

250
00:13:30.979 --> 00:13:33.330
a positive or a negative view of human nature.

251
00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:35.059
You know, you might look at the the human

252
00:13:35.059 --> 00:13:37.299
world as we know it and conclude that it's

253
00:13:37.299 --> 00:13:40.659
suffused with cruelty, arrogance, dogmatism, and all these other

254
00:13:40.659 --> 00:13:44.140
vices, but that's consistent with our being, um good

255
00:13:44.140 --> 00:13:46.500
by nature, but also without being bad by nature.

256
00:13:46.849 --> 00:13:49.080
I mean, it's perfectly possible that human beings could

257
00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:53.039
by nature be disposed towards kindness, generosity and trust,

258
00:13:53.049 --> 00:13:55.520
and the other other virtues. It's just that we

259
00:13:55.520 --> 00:13:58.760
get socialized within a corrupting world that tends to

260
00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:01.510
suppress our vices and draw out our failings. And

261
00:14:01.510 --> 00:14:03.349
for this reason, at least in my own work,

262
00:14:03.609 --> 00:14:07.390
I want to exclude human nature um from misanthropy.

263
00:14:07.640 --> 00:14:09.799
The judgment is not being passed on human nature,

264
00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:12.960
it's being passed on the collective structures and forms

265
00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:15.400
of human life, and at least in some cases.

266
00:14:15.820 --> 00:14:19.280
The concept of human nature becomes very problematic, either

267
00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:22.419
because people understand that concept in very one-sided ways,

268
00:14:22.710 --> 00:14:25.070
or they try to use it as a strategy

269
00:14:25.070 --> 00:14:29.150
for undermining misanthropy by insisting that even if collectively

270
00:14:29.150 --> 00:14:32.309
we're very bad, individually deep down, we are very,

271
00:14:32.349 --> 00:14:35.789
very good. But that's irrelevant to misanthropy because the

272
00:14:35.789 --> 00:14:38.020
question is not what are we like deep down,

273
00:14:38.169 --> 00:14:40.549
it's what are we like in large scale collective

274
00:14:40.549 --> 00:14:44.030
societies bound by institutions and practices. Um, WHAT we're

275
00:14:44.030 --> 00:14:46.289
like deep down is irrelevant to that. So I

276
00:14:46.289 --> 00:14:49.169
think that we should leave out human nature and

277
00:14:49.169 --> 00:14:51.409
not focus on individuals. It's being a jud the

278
00:14:51.409 --> 00:14:54.520
judgment is passed on the collective structures of human

279
00:14:54.520 --> 00:14:55.400
forms of life.

280
00:14:56.900 --> 00:15:00.940
OK, so that that's a very important clarification because

281
00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:05.369
I mean, I was thinking that. Uh, MAYBE I'm

282
00:15:05.369 --> 00:15:07.809
wrong, of course, but it could be the case

283
00:15:07.809 --> 00:15:10.049
that I'm wrong. But it is, it seems to

284
00:15:10.049 --> 00:15:15.570
me that most people, most of the time are

285
00:15:15.570 --> 00:15:19.890
decent. I'm not saying that, uh, there's, there's not

286
00:15:19.890 --> 00:15:23.710
any vices that all people tend to suffer a

287
00:15:23.710 --> 00:15:26.409
little bit from. I mean, I guess that every

288
00:15:26.409 --> 00:15:30.390
one of us suffers from at least a small

289
00:15:30.390 --> 00:15:34.590
number of vices, but isn't it, uh, I mean,

290
00:15:34.669 --> 00:15:40.590
when it comes to humanity's failures, isn't it mostly

291
00:15:40.590 --> 00:15:44.270
a small number of individuals that tend to be

292
00:15:44.270 --> 00:15:50.469
responsible for humanity's biggest, uh, failings or, or not?

293
00:15:50.510 --> 00:15:52.390
I mean, what do you think about that?

294
00:15:53.359 --> 00:15:55.719
Well, well I I think one advantage of using

295
00:15:55.719 --> 00:15:59.799
the term failings is that. Uh, IT doesn't bring

296
00:15:59.799 --> 00:16:01.590
to mind individuals in the ways that the term

297
00:16:01.590 --> 00:16:04.280
vices does. So, you know, in David's work, he

298
00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:06.200
says, I use the word failings because if you

299
00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:09.869
say vices, people immediately think of individuals, which then

300
00:16:09.869 --> 00:16:12.960
reinforces a misconception about misanthropy. Whereas I think we

301
00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:15.520
do talk quite naturally of the failings of institutions

302
00:16:15.520 --> 00:16:18.559
or societies. Um, SO failings, I think, is, is

303
00:16:18.559 --> 00:16:20.440
the more useful term. And it will be the

304
00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:23.000
case that there will be a dialectic between the

305
00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.919
vices of individuals and. Failings of social institutions. You

306
00:16:26.919 --> 00:16:29.630
know, for example, I take it, um, if you

307
00:16:29.630 --> 00:16:33.760
think that certain kinds of capitalist economy are greedy,

308
00:16:33.880 --> 00:16:38.200
exploitative, and destructive, well, those systems couldn't function without

309
00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:40.719
people who had at least some individual version of

310
00:16:40.719 --> 00:16:42.679
those failings. There has to be a dialectic between

311
00:16:42.679 --> 00:16:44.919
the individuals and the collectives. I mean, if people

312
00:16:44.919 --> 00:16:48.080
were genuinely incapable of greed, then you couldn't develop

313
00:16:48.080 --> 00:16:52.280
greed economic systems, or so I assume. Um, BUT,

314
00:16:52.469 --> 00:16:54.400
but to the claim that it's really a small

315
00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:57.030
number of individuals who are causing all the trouble,

316
00:16:57.359 --> 00:17:00.909
I think the misanthrop will be cautious about that,

317
00:17:01.359 --> 00:17:04.439
because there are, there are two standard ways historically

318
00:17:04.439 --> 00:17:06.199
that people have tried to push back against a

319
00:17:06.199 --> 00:17:09.358
misanthropic verdict. One is to is to acknowledge the

320
00:17:09.358 --> 00:17:12.800
reality of our failings, but confine them to unusually

321
00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:17.920
awful people, uh, psychopaths, moral monsters, dictators, tyrants. The

322
00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:20.598
other is to try to confine our failings only

323
00:17:20.598 --> 00:17:24.680
to certain unusually awful conditions like uh civil war,

324
00:17:24.729 --> 00:17:28.239
for example, or, or maybe conditions of poverty or

325
00:17:28.239 --> 00:17:31.760
society collapse. Now, of course, the misanthrop can acknowledge,

326
00:17:31.880 --> 00:17:33.719
there are some people and some groups who are

327
00:17:33.719 --> 00:17:37.680
unusually awful and bear a special responsibility for the

328
00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:40.900
worsening of human society. So if you're an ecom

329
00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:44.780
misanthrope, you might point to uh the big fossil

330
00:17:44.780 --> 00:17:47.699
fuel companies. You know, it's, it's not just that,

331
00:17:47.739 --> 00:17:50.500
uh, carbon intensive economic systems are causing a huge

332
00:17:50.500 --> 00:17:53.060
amount of environmental damage. We also know that they

333
00:17:53.060 --> 00:17:55.699
engage in doubt mongering, and they, they have been

334
00:17:55.699 --> 00:18:00.050
trying and succeeding to manipulate political and public understanding

335
00:18:00.339 --> 00:18:03.410
of the relationship between fossil fuels and climate change.

336
00:18:03.699 --> 00:18:07.099
And in his book, um, on environmental pessimism, Toby

337
00:18:07.099 --> 00:18:11.229
Svoboda says, Um, this doubt mongering about climate change

338
00:18:11.229 --> 00:18:13.819
is a genuine kind of evil because it causes

